node.text:
@mrs.shight I struggle to get my steps in but when i can get back to the office finally I know that walking there and back will be more than enough! I’ve gotten lazy in lockdown ?
Enjoy Cadbury world, sounds like a fun day out!xx
@being.imperfectly.perfect I think we all got a bit lazy - being stuck in the house is gonna do that. But now that I can get back out there I’m making the most of it ?
Definitely about balance! I work out with a PT once a week and walk 10,000+ steps a day, but I’m not going to miss going to Cadbury world next week ? ?
@gemmacorps me too! I actually felt that I had lost a little bit but my jeans were tighter than ever the other day when I put them on ??‍??xx

@being.imperfectly.perfect I haven’t even tried my jeans in about 10 weeks ? I just think m metabolism has slowed down now I’m not rushing around taking the kids to school etc. This month I’m making a bigger effort on watching what I eat but the husband has just come back from Waitrose with baileys flavoured biscuits ?
@gemmacorps it would be wrong to say no to those! They sound amazing!xx
Absolutely about balance! Especially at the moment. No point depriving yourself of something you fancy x

@being.imperfectly.perfect I haven’t even tried my jeans in about 10 weeks ? I just think m metabolism has slowed down now I’m not rushing around taking the kids to school etc. This month I’m making a bigger effort on watching what I eat but the husband has just come back from Waitrose with baileys flavoured biscuits ?
@gemmacorps it would be wrong to say no to those! They sound amazing!xx

I’m not sure that this entirely fits in to my attempts at healthy eating, although it’s not a McDonald’s which is what I really wanted so I guess that’s a step in the right direction!

Grilled lean bacon medallions and scrambled egg in a pitta, one with a slice of rubber cheese! 

If I’m honest I struggled to eat both of them, my appetite has shrunk since I’ve been more mindful about portion control.

I guess it’s about not depriving myself when I do fancy something that might be a little less healthy. 

Next week I’m going to start more regular exercise, so I’ll be back on the high protein cereal and yoghurt meaning I’ll be fuller for longer.

It’s all about balance, right?

node.text:
SOFT ROTIS
.
There’s nothing more charming than the smell of home-made rotis wafting through the kitchen, best part is that it’s a precursor to taste. Through the centuries, rotis has remained the cornerstone of the Indian community and culture.
This flatbread has been a casual distraction to the meal itself, yet without fail, it heroically feeds and nurtures our soul. It’s simple food, tugs at your heart, reminiscent of childhood meals for wraps, pizzas and the perfect remedy for sauce or gravy mopping situations. Eaten warm, sprinkled with sugar makes a lovely companion to your tea.
.
Profoundly this is the magic wonder of pantry staples, flour, salt and water. It’s the kind of recipe that you can make at the top of your head, and once you’ve made it, you’ll know it’s worth every time. Seductively soft, fluffy and totally irresistible! 
 .
The roti fame is nowhere near waning, you can shop the link in bio for the recipe in my ebook.
.
Follow @foodiesof_cakewalk for more photos and ideas/recipes. Tag me should you recreate any of my foods, I’d love to share them. .

node.text:
From May onwards, Different Strokes have been delighted to be in conversation with individual stroke survivors in lockdown; discussing how they are coping, what they’ve found challenging and how this experience has impacted them in all aspects of day to day life. The pre-recorded interviews take place via Zoom and are posted every Tuesday afternoon. You can find them all on the Different Strokes website, Facebook page and YouTube channel but a snippet of each already on the DS channels have also been posted to our feed to briefly introduce our wonderful Instagram audience and to give everyone a taster of personal affiliation with each survivor.

Lockdown interview number nine features stroke survivors Genise and Bridie. Genise is our Family Support Officer at Different Strokes. She had her stroke 21 years ago at the age of 34. Bridie is our Instagram volunteer and also did a successful takeover in January which she discusses in the interview. She had a thalamic stroke 10 years ago, aged 17. Bridie spoke to Genise about the issues she faces having left sided numbness and damage, along with her chronic pain condition, how lockdown has aggravated it, how it’s delayed appointments with her neurologist to keep monitoring and managing the pain with medications and how difficult it is not seeing him face to face. She talks about digesting the current news, missing her friends, the difficulties she will now face with the demand for work from home jobs, unravelling her creation and imagination during this period, celebrating a birthday during lockdown and how she’s looking forward to getting back into normal routine where the days stop mingling into one. She also chats about her aims going forward on the DS Instagram, how our befriending services would’ve been invaluable to her at the time of her stroke and how she hopes this year will open the eyes of abled people having a greater understanding whilst keeping up accessibilities and meeting the needs of those in need.

Catch the full interview at:⁣
